[[File:Ende Gelände 2017 CHB 23 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Environmental activist blocking the coal mine during Ende Gelände 2017.]]
'''Ende Gelände 2017''' was a large [[civil disobedience]] [[protest]] movement in Germany to [[Climate change mitigation|limit]] [[global warming]] through [[fossil fuel phase-out]].<ref name=Flening/><ref name=Watts/>
3,000-6,000 [[environmental activist]]s from several countries blocked two German [[Open-pit mining|open-pit]] [[Coal mining|coal mine]]s: * From 24 to 29 August 2017, about 6,000 persons blocked a mine owned by [[RWE]] in the [[Rhineland]] coalfields.<ref>[https://www.ende-gelaende.org/en/press-release/press-release-august-30-2017/ "Action days in the Rhineland coalfields come to a close + 6000 people in diverse and powerful protest against lignite mining"], press release of Ende Gelände, 30 August 2017 (page visited on 12 January 2018).</ref><ref name=Flening>Molly Flening, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/climate-change-activists-germany-police-cologne-brutality-pepper-spray-global-warming-a7922656.html "Thousands of climate activists face police brutality in Germany"], ''[[The Independent]]'', 31 August 2017 (page visited on 12 January 2018).</ref>
* On 5 November 2017 (for the [[2017 United Nations Climate Change Conference]]), around 3,000 persons blocked the [[Hambach lignite mine]].<ref>[https://www.ende-gelaende.org/en/press-release/press-release-7-11-2017/ "On Sunday Ende Gelände successfully blocked the Hambach lignite mine"], press release of Ende Gelände, 7 November 2017 (page visited on 12 January 2018).</ref><ref name=Watts>Jonathan Watts, [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/nov/08/germanys-dirty-coalmines-become-the-focus-for-a-new-wave-of-direct-action "Germany's dirty coalmines become the focus for a new wave of direct action"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 November 2017 (page visited on 12 January 2018).</ref>
== Context == On 15 August 2015, in the first year of Ende Gelände, 1,500 activists blocked the [[Garzweiler surface mine]] owned by [[RWE]] (Ende Gelände 2015).<ref>John Jordan, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/27/europes-biggest-polluter-protesters-lignite-mine-germany-direct-action "The day we stopped Europe's biggest polluter in its tracks"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', Thursday 27 August 2015 (page visited in 28 September 2016).</ref><ref>[https://350.org/ende-gelande-wrap-up/ Ende Gelände 2015], [[350.org]] (page visited in 28 September 2016).</ref>
On 13 to 15 May 2016, with [[Ende Gelände 2016]], 4,000 activists blocked the Welzow-Süd [[Open-pit mining|open-pit]] [[Coal mining|coal mine]] and the coal-fired [[Schwarze Pumpe power station]], then owned by [[Vattenfall]] ([[Spremberg]]).<ref name=Release>[https://www.ende-gelaende.org/en/press-release/press-release-15-may-2016/ Mass action blocking German lignite mining finishes after 48 hours], press release of Ende Gelände, 15 May 2016 (page visited in 28 September 2016).</ref>
