In [[Politics of Austria|Austrian politics]], the '''Ministry of Sustainability and Tourism''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Bundesministerium für Nachhaltigkeit und Tourismus'' or ''BMNT'', although often called ''Nachhaltigkeitsministerium'' <ref name="s1">{{cite web | url = https://derstandard.at/suche/?query=nachhaltigkeitsministerium&ressortId=0&status=AktivArchiv&period=All | title = Der Standard archive search | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | date = May 6, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="s2">{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/user/search.do?resetForm=1&resultsPage=0&searchText=nachhaltigkeitsministerium | title = Die Presse archive search | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | date = May 6, 2018 }}</ref>)
is the [[ministry (government)|ministry]] in charge of agricultural policy, forestry, hunting, fishing, viticulture and wine law, environmental protection, energy, mining, animal welfare, and the tourism industry.<ref name="bmgnov">{{cite act | title = Bundesministeriengesetz-Novelle 2017 | type = BGBl. I | number = 164/2017 | url = https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/eli/bgbl/I/2017/164/20171228 | language = German | date = December 28, 2017 | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref> <!-- note this is the date of promulgation, not of adoption -->
The Ministry was first created in 2000 through a merger of the [[Ministry of Agriculture (Austria)|Ministry of Agriculture]] (''Landwirtschaftsministerium'') and the [[Ministry of Environment (Austria)|Ministry of Environment]] (''Umweltministerium''); it gained responsibility for the energy sector, mining, and tourism under the [[Kurz government|Kurz cabinet]] in 2018.

The current Minister of Sustainability and Tourism is [[Elisabeth Köstinger]].<ref name="neu">{{cite web | url = https://kurier.at/politik/inland/tuerkis-blau-i-das-sind-die-neuen-minister/302.322.267 | title = Türkis-Blau: Das sind die neuen Minister | date = December 16, 2017 | publisher = Kurier | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref><ref name="orf">{{cite web | url = http://orf.at/stories/2419283/2419284/ | title = 16-köpfiges ÖVP-FPÖ-Team vereidigt | date = December 16, 2017 | publisher = ORF | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref><ref name="cv">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmvit.gv.at/en/ministerium/hofer.html | title = Curriculum Vitae of the Federal Minister Norbert Hofer | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | publisher = BMVIT }}</ref><ref name="m3">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmnt.gv.at/ministerium/die-ministerin.html | title = Die Minsterin | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | language = German | publisher = BMNT | date = March 19, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="struktur">{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/home/innenpolitik/5380688/Koestinger-gibt-ihrem-Landwirtschaftsministerium-neue | date = January 3, 2018 | publisher = Die Presse | language = German | title = Köstinger gibt Landwirtschaftsministerium neue Organisationsstruktur | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref>

== History ==

The Ministry's earliest precursor was the [[Cisleithania]]n [[Ministry of Agriculture (Austria)|Ministry of Agriculture]] (''Ackerbauministerium''), created in 1867. In additional to agriculture, the Ministry was responsible for regulating hunting, fishing, and hydraulic engineering, excluding hydraulic engineering of military importance.<ref name="m1">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmnt.gv.at/ministerium/geschichte-LM/geschichteLM.html | title = Geschichte des Ministeriums | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | date = January 16, 2018 | publisher = BMNT | language = German }}</ref><ref name="geschichte">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmnt.gv.at/ministerium/geschichte-LM/150-jahre-landwirtschaftsministerium.html | title = 150 Jahre Landwirtschaftsminiterium | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | date = April 4, 2018 | language = German | publisher = BMNT }}</ref>
The organization was renamed to Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry (''Ministerium für Land- und Forstwirtschaft'') in 1918 and was briefly called a department (''Staatsamt'') rather than a ministry during the two periods of constitutional transition following the two World Wars. Except for the name, however, the Ministry survived mostly in its original form until 2000.

In 1972, Austria established the [[Ministry of Health (Austria)|Ministry of Health and the Environment]] (''Ministerium für Gesundheit und Umweltschutz'', usually called ''Gesundheitsministerium'' or ''Umweltministerium'' for short). In 1987, family affairs were added to its portfolio, turning it into the Ministry of Environment, Youth and Family Affairs (''Ministerium für Umwelt, Jugend und Familie'') <ref name="m1"/><ref name="history">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmnt.gv.at/english/ministry/History-of-the-Ministry/History-of-the-Ministry.html | title = History of the Ministry | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | publisher = BMNT | date = January 16, 2018 }}</ref>

In 2000, the two ministries were combined to form the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, Environment and Water Management (''Ministerium für Land- und Forstwirtschaft, Umwelt und Wasserwirtschaft'', although often called ''Lebensministerium'').<ref name="history"/> Responsibility for family affairs was moved to the Ministry of Social Affairs (''Sozialministerium'') at the time.

When the [[Kurz government|Kurz cabinet]] took office in December 2017, the ministry was put in charge of the energy sector, mining, and tourism in addition to its existing powers and duties; it also gained its current designation.<ref name="geschichte"/><ref name="history"/><ref name="angelobt">{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/home/innenpolitik/5349890/Acht-Minister-erneut-angelobt | title = Acht Minister neu angelobt | publisher = Die Presse | language = German | date = January 8, 2018 | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref>
The additional responsibilities created an institution with exceptionally broad authority; the new ministry has been described as a "super ministry" (''Superministerium'') <ref name="supermin">{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/home/wirtschaft/economist/5356687/Warum-Landwirtschaft-im-Superministerium-von-Koestinger-keinen | title = Warum Landwirtschaft im Superministerium von Köstinger keinen Platz hat | date = January 19, 2018 | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | publisher = Die Presse | language = German }}</ref> and a "behemoth" (''Riese''); the cabinet had difficulties finding a new name that would adequately reflect its extensive purview, the present minister has noted.<ref name="supermin"/>
The move was not completely uncontroversial.<ref name="unmut">{{cite web | url = https://diepresse.com/home/innenpolitik/5339713/Kurz-Minister_Wie-sie-wurden-was-sie-nun-sind | accessdate = 2016-05-08 | date = December 16, 2017 | title = Kurz' Minister: Wie sie wurden, was sie nun sind | publisher = Die Presse | language = German }}</ref>

== Responsibilities ==

As of January 2018, the Ministry is charged with regulating, supervising, or managing, respectively:<ref name="bmgconsolidated">{{cite web | title = Bundesministeriengesetz 1986 in der Fassung vom 28. Dezember 2017 | url = https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/GeltendeFassung.wxe?Abfrage=Bundesnormen&Gesetzesnummer=10000873 | date = December 28, 2017 | publisher = BKA | accessdate = 2018-05-06 | language = German }}</ref>
* agricultural policy and law;
* the food sector with the exception of food safety;
* forestry policy and law;
* domestic markets for agricultural, food and forestry products, including seeds and seed stock, animal food, fertilizer, plant protection products, including their regulatory approval, with the exception of price regulation, surveillance, and control;
* imports and exports;
* wine law and viticultural supervision;
* land reform; agricultural authorities; agricultural and forestry real estate transactions; 
* measures aimed at reducing the agriculture and forestry sector's exposure to debt;
* water law and water management with the exception of the engineering aspects of waterway, water supply, and sewerage construction;
* plant protection;
* agricultural and forestry schools, including human resources management, to the extent not handles by the [[Federal Chancellery (Austria)|Chancellery]];
* agricultural and forestry commodity exchanges;
* professional representation of agricultural and forestry entrepreneurs and freelancers;
* management of public real estate used for agriculture and forestry;
* hunting and fishing;
* protecting Austria's border waters and safeguarding Austria's water rights and water management interests; engineering aspects of water construction in border waters, with the exception of the [[Danube]], the March, and the [[Thaya]] downstream from [[Bernhardsthal]];
* climate and environmental protection;
* waste management and rehabilitation of contaminated sites;
* species conservation;
* protection of natural caves;
* protection from ionizing radiation;
* traffic and commerce in poisonous substances;
* the energy sector, excepting matters within the purview of the [[Ministry of Economy (Austria)|Ministry of Digital and Economic Affairs]];
* mining;
* tourism.

== Structure ==

As of May 2018, the ministry consists of the Minister and her personal staff (''Kabinett''), the office of the general secretary, a special coordination department, and six numbered regular departments (''Sektionen''):<ref name="org">{{cite web | url = https://www.bmnt.gv.at/ministerium/aufgaben-struktur.html | title = Aufgaben und Struktur dem BMNT | publisher = BMNT | language = German | accessdate = 2018-05-06 }}</ref>
# Environmental and climate protection (''Umwelt und Klimaschutz'')
# Agriculture and rural development (''Landwirtschaft und ländliche Entwicklung'')
# Forestry (''Forstwirtschaft'')
# Water management and hydraulic engineering (''Wasserwirtschaft'')
# Waste management, chemicals policy, and environmental technology (''Abfallwirtschaft, Chemiepolitik und Umwelttechnologie'')
# Energy and mining (''Energie und Bergbau'')

The Minister and her staff are political appointees; the general secretary and the section heads are career civil servants.

