{{Infobox philosopher |region = |era = |color = lightsteelblue |image = Robert Vitas One.jpg |image_size = |caption = |name = Robert Vitas |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = |main_interests = Military Sociology, [[Civil-Military Relations]] |notable_ideas = |influences = |influenced = |signature = }}
'''Robert A. Vitas''' is a scholar of [[civil-military relations]], [[National Security Strategy (United States)|national security strategy]], and [[Lithuania]] studies. He was an army officer in the [[U.S. Army Reserve]] and a visiting scholar at [[Northwestern University]]. He is currently the executive director of the [[Inter-University Seminar on Armed Forces and Society|Inter-University Seminar on Armed Forces & Society]]. He is also the chairman of the [[Lithuanian Research and Studies Center]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.lithuanianresearch.org/eng/ltsceng/about.htm|publisher=Lithuanian Research and Studies Center|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref> He received his PhD from [[Loyola University Chicago]] and has produced scholarship with other notable civil-military relations scholars such as [[John Allen Williams (professor)|John Allen Williams]] and [[Sam C. Sarkesian]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Executive Officer|url=http://www.iusafs.org/leadership/XO.asp|publisher=IUSAFS|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>
==Notable Publications==
*U.S. National Security Policy and Strategy: Documents and Policy Proposals, Volume Two, 1986-1994. Westport, CT: [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood]], 1996. Co-editor with John Allen Williams. * The United States and Lithuania: The Stimson Doctrine of Nonrecognition. New York: [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Praeger]], 1990, 176 pp. Author. * U.S. National Security Policy and Strategy: Documents and Policy Proposals. [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood]], CT: Greenwood Press, 1988, 441 pp.&nbsp;Co-editor with Sam C. Sarkesian. * Pedagoginis Lituanistikos Institutas 1958-1983 (Lithuanian Institute of Education 1958-1983). Chicago: Lithuanian Institute of Education, 1984, 152 pp. Editor. * Civil-Military Relations in Lithuania Under President Antanas Smetona 1926-1940. Chicago: Lithuanian Research and Studies Center, 2004. * “Civilian Graduate Education and the Professional Officer,” Military Review, 89, 3 (May–June 1999), pp.&nbsp;47–58. Author. Later translated into Chinese by the Taiwan Ministry of Defense for use in officer education. * "The Recognition of Lithuania: The Completion of the Legal Circle." Journal of Baltic Studies, 24, 3 (Fall 1993), pp.&nbsp;247–262. Author. * "The Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact." The Observer, 5, 9 (September 1988), pp.&nbsp;6–7. Author.<ref>[http://www.google.com/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&ix=seb&ie=UTF-8&ion=1#hl=en&output=search&sclient=psy-ab&q=Robert%20vitas&pbx=1&oq=&aq=&aqi=&aql=&gs_sm=&gs_upl=&fp=c134f03b0cb322db&ix=seb&ion=1&ix=seb&ion=1&bav=on.2,or.r_gc.r_pw.r_qf.,cf.osb&fp=c134f03b0cb322db&biw=908&bih=815&ix=seb&ion=1 Curriculum Vitae] - Robert Vitas</ref>
